            {
              "id": "01f8ab43-a08f-38e9-bb85-86bdc535d929",
              "name": "Formatted SQL Query",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in a formatted database query. This Python code builds an SQL statement by inserting username and password directly into the query string with .format(), which allows attacker-controlled input to change the query structure.\n\nIn Python DB-API code such as sqlite3, values must be passed separately from the SQL text. For the sink shown here, bind the username and password as parameters in the execute() call so the database treats them as data instead of executable SQL. This prevents quotes, operators, and other special characters in input from altering the WHERE clause or bypassing authentication.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not construct SQL with string formatting, concatenation, f-strings, or %-formatting when any part comes from input. Use parameterized queries consistently for every variable value, and keep SQL structure static. If this query is part of authentication, also avoid storing raw passwords; store password hashes with a dedicated password hashing library and verify them separately after retrieving the account by username.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nuser = c.execute(\n    \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\",\n    (username, password),\n).fetchone()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0a0f537f-17b7-3790-b70e-89a18ca6e345",
              "name": "Sql Injection Via String Formatting",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in database execution. This code builds an INSERT statement by interpolating Python values directly into the SQL string before passing it to execute. If username or password contains quotes or SQL syntax, the database may interpret that input as part of the command instead of as data.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, values must be supplied separately from the SQL text so the driver can bind them safely. For the shown insert, keep the SQL statement static and pass a parameter tuple to execute. This prevents attacker-controlled input from changing the query structure and also avoids quoting and type-conversion bugs.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for all SQL values and never assemble SQL with %, str.format(), f-strings, or string concatenation. Keep the SQL command text constant and pass user-controlled data in the parameters argument supported by the Python database driver. For sqlite3, use ? placeholders; for other DB-API drivers, use that driver's documented parameter style.\n\nApply the same pattern to execute, executemany, and any query helper methods. If table names, column names, or sort directions must vary, do not pass them from user input directly; map allowed values from a fixed application-side allowlist. Validate input before database use, hash passwords before storing them, and run the application with the least database privileges required.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\nparams = (u, p, 0, 0, \"\")\nc.execute(sql, params)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249 - Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1c747a52-dc56-3fd6-b7a4-396cd7c05fe9",
              "name": "Insecure Password Storage in SQL Authentication",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is insecure password authentication with plaintext credential comparison. The code builds a SQL query that matches the supplied password directly against a database password column, which indicates passwords are being stored or handled in a form that can be compared verbatim.\n\nIn Python, this pattern is especially risky because the shown query is also constructed with string formatting, allowing attacker-controlled input to alter the SQL statement. Authentication should not be performed by asking the database to compare raw passwords. Instead, fetch the account record by username with a parameterized query, store a strong password hash in the database, and verify the submitted password in application code using a dedicated password-hashing library such as Argon2.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nStore only salted, adaptive password hashes, not plaintext passwords or reversible encrypted passwords. Use a well-vetted password hashing library such as Argon2 and keep authentication logic in Python rather than embedding password comparison into SQL.\n\nAlways use parameterized queries for all database access, including login flows. Query by a unique identifier such as username, retrieve the stored password hash, and verify the submitted password with the hashing library's verify function. If the current schema contains a password column with plaintext values, migrate users to a password_hash column and force password resets or rehash on next successful login.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom argon2 import PasswordHasher\nfrom argon2.exceptions import VerifyMismatchError\nimport sqlite3\n\nph = PasswordHasher()\n\nconn = sqlite3.connect(\"app.db\")\nc = conn.cursor()\n\ndef authenticate(username: str, password: str):\n    row = c.execute(\n        \"SELECT id, username, password_hash FROM users WHERE username = ?\",\n        (username,)\n    ).fetchone()\n\n    if row is None:\n        return None\n\n    user_id, db_username, password_hash = row\n\n    try:\n        ph.verify(password_hash, password)\n    except VerifyMismatchError:\n        return None\n\n    if ph.check_needs_rehash(password_hash):\n        new_hash = ph.hash(password)\n        c.execute(\n            \"UPDATE users SET password_hash = ? WHERE id = ?\",\n            (new_hash, user_id)\n        )\n        conn.commit()\n\n    return {\n        \"id\": user_id,\n        \"username\": db_username,\n    }\n\n# Example for creating a user securely:\ndef create_user(username: str, password: str):\n    password_hash = ph.hash(password)\n    c.execute(\n        \"INSERT INTO users (username, password_hash) VALUES (?, ?)\",\n        (username, password_hash)\n    )\n    conn.commit()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nargon2-cffi\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-256: Plaintext Storage of a Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [argon2-cffi Documentation](https://argon2-cffi.readthedocs.io/en/stable/)\n- [Python sqlite3 Module Documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-256",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-256",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1d3afeb2-7abf-3713-88ad-64d50148996d",
              "name": "Formatted SQL Query",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection risk. This code builds an INSERT statement by formatting user-controlled values directly into the SQL string before calling execute. In Python DB-API code, string interpolation does not separate code from data, so crafted input in fields such as username or password can alter the query or break its syntax.\n\nThe fix is to use a parameterized query and pass the values as a separate argument to execute. For this sink, keep the SQL text static and bind username, password, and the other values through placeholders supported by the Python database driver. This ensures the driver encodes values safely and preserves the intended INSERT behavior.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not use %, f-strings, format(), or string concatenation to assemble SQL statements with variable data. Use the placeholder style required by the active Python DB-API driver and pass parameters separately to execute or executemany. Keep SQL structure fixed, validate input against expected formats and lengths, and store passwords with a strong password hashing function rather than inserting raw password values into the database.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\nc.execute(sql, (username, password, 0, 0, \"\"))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249: Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "211b77d1-5ab4-3059-9610-518839d10e22",
              "name": "Formatted SQL Query",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection risk through string-formatted database queries. In Python, building SQL with % string interpolation mixes code and data in the same statement, so any value that later becomes user-controlled can alter the query structure instead of being stored as data.\n\nThe sink shown constructs an INSERT statement by formatting values directly into the SQL string before calling execute(). Even if some current values are empty strings or constants, this pattern is unsafe and brittle because future changes can introduce attacker-controlled input. The correct fix is to keep the SQL text static and pass values separately using DB-API parameters so the driver binds them safely.\n\nFor this INSERT, replace the formatted query with placeholders and supply a parameter tuple to execute(). This preserves the intended values for username, password, salt, failures, mfa_enabled, and mfa_secret without allowing quoting or escaping mistakes to change the SQL command.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for all database reads and writes, including INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and SELECT. Never assemble SQL with %, f-strings, format(), or string concatenation when inserting variable data. Validate input according to business rules, but do not rely on validation or escaping as a substitute for bound parameters. Keep SQL statements static, pass values through the database driver's parameter API, and use least-privileged database accounts to limit impact if a query path is abused.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, salt, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\nparams = (username, '', '', 0, 0, '')\nc.execute(sql, params)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249: Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "392f9e1d-b706-3257-afad-70ed0cdae2ba",
              "name": "Formatted SQL Query",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in a database execute call. This statement builds an INSERT query with Python string formatting and then sends the final SQL text to the database. If any interpolated value comes from user-controlled input, an attacker can alter the SQL structure, bypass intended data handling, or write unexpected data.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, values must be passed separately from the SQL string so the driver can bind them as parameters instead of treating them as SQL syntax. For the shown sink, replace string interpolation with placeholders and provide a parameter tuple to execute(). Keep constants such as the failure count as bound values as well for consistency and safety.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not assemble SQL with %, f-strings, str.format, or string concatenation. Use the parameter style required by the active Python database driver and pass user input as bound parameters. Validate input for business rules such as length and allowed characters, but do not rely on validation instead of parameterization. If table or column names must be dynamic, select them from a fixed allowlist because SQL identifiers cannot be safely bound as value parameters. Store passwords with a dedicated password-hashing function rather than inserting plaintext credentials into the database.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nc.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO users (user, password, failures) VALUES (?, ?, ?)\",\n    (u, p, 0),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249: Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3ac8edf6-5510-3295-b417-abbf726cd12c",
              "name": "Debug Mode Enabled In Production Environment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an active debug mode in production issue. In Python Flask applications, running the development server with debug enabled exposes detailed error pages, stack traces, configuration details, and other internal state that can disclose sensitive information to users.\n\nIn the shown sink, app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', ssl_context=('/tmp/acme.cert', '/tmp/acme.key')) explicitly enables debug mode at runtime. Even when TLS is configured, the debugger and verbose error handling remain enabled. For deployed environments, disable debug mode and read the setting from application configuration or environment variables so production runs with safe defaults.\n\nFlask's built-in server is intended for development. For production, keep DEBUG disabled and run the application behind a production WSGI server, while preserving certificate handling and host binding through deployment configuration rather than hard-coded debug flags.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hard-code debug=True in deployed code. Set DEBUG to false by default and enable it only in local development through environment-specific configuration. Avoid exposing interactive debuggers or detailed exception pages to end users, and use Flask's built-in server only for development. In production, serve the app with a production WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI and manage TLS, host binding, and environment settings outside the application entry point.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config[\"DEBUG\"] = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(\n        debug=app.config[\"DEBUG\"],\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        ssl_context=(\"/tmp/acme.cert\", \"/tmp/acme.key\")\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\ngunicorn\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Flask Documentation: Debug Mode](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#debug-mode)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation: Debugger](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [OWASP: Information Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Information_exposure_through_query_strings_in_url)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "50d955cf-aed7-3643-802d-3b3c0af65a93",
              "name": "Direct Write To SQL Password Column",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure password storage. This code writes a raw password value directly into the database, which exposes user credentials if the database is leaked, backed up insecurely, or accessed by unauthorized users.\n\nIn Python, passwords should never be stored in plaintext or with reversible encryption. Derive a one-way password hash using a password hashing algorithm designed for credential storage, such as bcrypt, and store only the resulting hash. For this sink, the SQL statement should also be parameterized so the password hash and username are bound safely instead of being interpolated into the query string.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse a dedicated password hashing algorithm such as bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2 with a per-password salt and a work factor appropriate for your deployment. Store only the derived hash, never the original password, and verify passwords with the library’s comparison function rather than reimplementing hash checks. In Python DB-API code, always use parameterized queries instead of string formatting to prevent SQL injection while updating credential fields.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport bcrypt\n\npassword_hash = bcrypt.hashpw(password.encode(\"utf-8\"), bcrypt.gensalt()).decode(\"utf-8\")\nc.execute(\n    \"UPDATE users SET password = ? WHERE username = ?\",\n    (password_hash, username),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nbcrypt\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-256: Plaintext Storage of a Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html)\n- [Python hashlib documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/hashlib.html)\n- [bcrypt for Python](https://pypi.org/project/bcrypt/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-256",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-256"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "562777b9-358d-3dca-8b3f-f4d770c0ed21",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in database query construction. This code builds an INSERT statement by interpolating Python values directly into the SQL string before calling execute(), which allows data to change the structure of the query instead of being treated strictly as data.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, string formatting must not be used to assemble SQL statements. Even if some fields appear constant or are expected to contain simple text, an attacker-controlled username or future code change can introduce malicious SQL fragments, break quoting, or corrupt data. The fix is to use parameterized queries so the database driver sends values separately from the SQL command.\n\nFor this sink, replace %-formatting with placeholders supported by the driver and pass the values as a separate parameter tuple or mapping. If this code uses SQLAlchemy, use text() with named parameters or the ORM/Core expression APIs instead of composing raw SQL strings.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for all SQL statements, including INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and SELECT. Keep SQL syntax static and provide untrusted values through the database driver's parameter binding API. Do not rely on manual escaping, quote replacement, or input filtering as a substitute for bound parameters.\n\nWhere practical, prefer higher-level database abstractions such as SQLAlchemy ORM or SQL Expression Language to reduce direct string-based SQL construction. Also enforce least-privilege database accounts and validate input for business rules, but treat validation as complementary to parameterization, not a replacement.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = (\n    \"INSERT INTO users \"\n    \"(username, password, salt, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) \"\n    \"VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\n)\n\nc.execute(sql, (username, '', '', 0, 0, ''))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy text() and bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5bc6ae87-e185-30ac-baaa-aba35344c69a",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. This code starts a Python web application with an SSL certificate and private key loaded from predictable paths under /tmp. Files in shared temporary directories are vulnerable to tampering, replacement, symlink attacks, and unintended disclosure if permissions are not tightly controlled.\n\nIn this sink, the private key path is especially sensitive. An attacker on the same system may be able to pre-create, replace, or read files in /tmp depending on filesystem protections and process privileges. The call also enables debug mode, which is not appropriate for production-facing TLS service startup. Store certificate material in a dedicated non-temporary directory with restrictive permissions, and run the server without debug enabled.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place certificates, private keys, session files, or other security-sensitive assets in world-writable temporary directories such as /tmp. Use a dedicated application-owned directory outside temporary storage, set ownership to the service account, and restrict the private key to owner-only permissions such as 0o600. If temporary files are truly required elsewhere in the application, create them with Python's tempfile module and keep handles open to reduce race conditions.\n\nDisable debug mode for deployed services. Prefer terminating TLS in a production-grade web server or reverse proxy, or at minimum ensure the Python process reads key material from stable, access-controlled paths. Validate file existence, type, and permissions before starting the listener so the application fails closed when TLS assets are misconfigured.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\n\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\ncert_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls/server.crt\")\nkey_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls/server.key\")\n\nfor path in (cert_path, key_path):\n    st = path.stat()\n    if not path.is_file():\n        raise RuntimeError(f\"Missing TLS file: {path}\")\n    if path == key_path and (st.st_mode & 0o077):\n        raise RuntimeError(\"TLS private key permissions must be restricted to the owner\")\n\napp.run(\n    debug=False,\n    host=\"127.0.0.1\",\n    ssl_context=(str(cert_path), str(key_path)),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Flask Development Server](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/server/)\n- [Werkzeug Serving Documentation](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/serving/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6ed74063-0b6a-3c5b-8c43-7aed4374390b",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in a database update query. This code builds an UPDATE statement by formatting untrusted values directly into the SQL string, which allows crafted input in username or password to change the structure of the query.\n\nIn Python DB-API code such as sqlite3, string formatting is not a safe way to pass data into SQL. The fix is to keep SQL text static and bind user-controlled values as parameters so the database treats them as data, not executable SQL. For this sink, replace .format(...) with a parameterized execute call using placeholders supported by the driver.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for every database operation that includes external input, including SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE. Do not use string concatenation, f-strings, percent formatting, or str.format to assemble SQL. In Python, follow the placeholder style required by the active database driver and pass values in the separate parameters argument.\n\nWhere queries become more complex, prefer a higher-level database library or ORM that preserves parameter binding automatically. Also validate input for expected format and length, run database accounts with least privilege, and avoid exposing detailed SQL errors to users.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nc.execute(\n    \"UPDATE users SET password = ? WHERE username = ?\",\n    (password, username),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "95951740-38ff-305b-aae8-49306fa2b0d3",
              "name": "Formatted SQL Query",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in database update code. This statement builds an UPDATE query by formatting untrusted values directly into the SQL string before passing it to execute(). In Python DB-API code, string formatting does not separate code from data, so a crafted username or password can change the query structure, update unintended rows, or execute additional logic allowed by the driver.\n\nReplace formatted SQL with a parameterized statement and pass the values as a separate argument tuple. For the sink shown here, keep the SQL text static and use placeholders for password and username so the database driver binds them safely as data instead of parsing them as SQL syntax.\n\nAfter converting to parameters, preserve normal transaction handling and check the affected row count if the update is security-sensitive. This avoids injection while keeping the update behavior explicit and predictable in Python.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nNever assemble SQL with format(), f-strings, percent formatting, or string concatenation when any part comes from runtime input. In Python, use the parameter style required by the active DB driver and pass values separately to execute() or executemany(). Keep SQL structure constant, allow user input only in bound parameters, and use allowlisted mapping if table or column names must vary. Store passwords as strong password hashes before writing them to the database, and run database operations with the least privileges needed.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"UPDATE users SET password = ? WHERE username = ?\"\nc.execute(sql, (password, username))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "B108",
              "name": "hardcoded_tmp_directory",
