            {
              "id": "a3e25d77-cf1f-3d7f-823d-0f5f469e5830",
              "name": "Debug Mode Enabled In Production Environment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an active debug mode in production issue. In Python Flask applications, running the development server with debug enabled exposes detailed error pages, stack traces, configuration details, and other internal state that can disclose sensitive information to users.\n\nIn the shown sink, app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', ssl_context=('/tmp/acme.cert', '/tmp/acme.key')) explicitly enables debug mode at runtime. Even when TLS is configured, the debugger and verbose error handling remain enabled. For deployed environments, disable debug mode and read the setting from application configuration or environment variables so production runs with safe defaults.\n\nFlask's built-in server is intended for development. For production, keep DEBUG disabled and run the application behind a production WSGI server, while preserving certificate handling and host binding through deployment configuration rather than hard-coded debug flags.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hard-code debug=True in deployed code. Set DEBUG to false by default and enable it only in local development through environment-specific configuration. Avoid exposing interactive debuggers or detailed exception pages to end users, and use Flask's built-in server only for development. In production, serve the app with a production WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI and manage TLS, host binding, and environment settings outside the application entry point.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\napp.config[\"DEBUG\"] = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(\n        debug=app.config[\"DEBUG\"],\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        ssl_context=(\"/tmp/acme.cert\", \"/tmp/acme.key\")\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\ngunicorn\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Flask Documentation: Debug Mode](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#debug-mode)\n- [Werkzeug Documentation: Debugger](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debug/)\n- [OWASP: Information Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Information_exposure_through_query_strings_in_url)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a6714b42-42f7-365d-9f83-369e1ed7e281",
              "name": "Formatted SQL Query",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection through string-formatted database queries. In Python, building an SQL statement with % formatting mixes untrusted values directly into the command text before it is sent to the database. If username or password contains SQL metacharacters, the query can be altered, causing unauthorized data access or modification.\n\nFor this execute call, the fix is to keep the SQL text static and pass user-controlled values as bound parameters. Python DB-API drivers handle quoting and escaping for parameter values, and integer constants can be passed as parameters as well. This preserves the intended INSERT statement and prevents input from changing its structure.\n\nStoring passwords directly is also unsafe. Insert a strong password hash instead of the raw password value, and generate MFA secrets only when needed rather than defaulting to a predictable empty string.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for every database operation and never compose SQL with string interpolation, concatenation, f-strings, or %-formatting. Keep SQL statements constant and pass all variable data through the driver parameter API appropriate for the Python database adapter in use.\n\nValidate input for length and expected format, but do not rely on validation alone to stop SQL injection. Apply least-privilege database accounts, avoid exposing detailed database errors to users, and hash passwords with a dedicated password hashing function before storage, such as bcrypt, scrypt, Argon2, or PBKDF2 with a strong work factor.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport hashlib\nimport os\n\nsalt = os.urandom(16)\npassword_hash = hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac(\"sha256\", p.encode(\"utf-8\"), salt, 600000).hex()\n\nc.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\",\n    (u, password_hash, 0, 0, \"\")\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nhashlib\nos\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249 - Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "bda5d5d5-4a18-34bb-a643-64808a1a484d",
              "name": "SQL Injection Through String-Based Query Construction",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in Python database access. This code builds an INSERT statement by interpolating user-controlled values directly into the SQL string before passing it to execute, which allows crafted input to change the intended query structure and write unintended data.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, values must be passed separately from the SQL text so the driver can bind them as data instead of parsing them as SQL. For the sink shown here, replace string formatting with a parameterized statement and provide the values as a tuple to execute.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for all database operations and never compose SQL with %, f-strings, format, or string concatenation when any part can vary at runtime. Keep SQL structure static, bind values through the database driver, and apply the placeholder style required by the specific Python driver in use. Also validate expected input shape at the application boundary, use least-privilege database accounts, and avoid exposing raw database errors to users.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nc.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO users (user, password, failures) VALUES (?, ?, ?)\",\n    (u, p, 0),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c670564b-1b0c-366a-8a6e-51c7b633614e",
              "name": "Sql Injection Via String Formatting",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in Python database access. This code builds a SQL query by inserting username and password directly into the statement with .format() before passing it to execute(). If either value contains SQL syntax, an attacker can change the meaning of the query, bypass authentication, or read and modify data.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, user input must be passed as query parameters rather than merged into the SQL string. For the sink shown here, keep the SQL text static and supply username and password separately so the database driver treats them as data, not executable SQL.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for every value that comes from a user, request, cookie, header, or other untrusted source. Do not use %, .format(), f-strings, or string concatenation to assemble SQL statements. In Python, follow the parameter style required by the database driver and pass values in the second argument to execute() or executemany().\n\nAlso avoid storing or comparing plaintext passwords in the database. Store password hashes using a strong password hashing function such as bcrypt, scrypt, or Argon2, and verify the supplied password against the stored hash. Apply least-privilege database accounts and server-side input validation as defense in depth, but rely on parameter binding as the primary fix for injection.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nuser = c.execute(\n    \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\",\n    (username, password),\n).fetchone()\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\nbcrypt\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249: Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c838b9ae-7158-3a0f-85a1-ae1641f89dad",
              "name": "Debug Mode Enabled In Production Environment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis issue is an enabled debug mode in a production web application. In Flask, setting debug=True starts the interactive debugger and detailed error pages, which can expose stack traces, configuration values, environment data, and other sensitive internals to users who should never see them.\n\nIn Python Flask applications, debug behavior should not be hardcoded at the app.run call site. In the shown sink, app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', port=5001, extra_files='csp.txt') forces debug mode on every time the process starts. Replace the hardcoded flag with configuration driven by environment variables and default to a non-debug production setting so the application does not accidentally launch with verbose diagnostics enabled.\n\nFor local development, enable debugging only through explicit environment-based configuration. For production, run the app with debug disabled and use a proper WSGI server and application configuration rather than relying on the built-in development server settings.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hardcode debug=True in Flask startup code. Make debug mode opt-in through environment configuration, default it to disabled, and keep it enabled only in local development. Avoid exposing the Werkzeug debugger or detailed exception pages to end users. For production deployments, run the Flask app behind a production-grade WSGI server such as gunicorn or uWSGI and manage environment-specific settings through configuration files or environment variables. Review other development-only options at startup, including reload behavior and watched files, so they are not unintentionally enabled in production.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    debug = os.getenv(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", \"0\") == \"1\"\n    app.run(host=\"127.0.1.1\", port=5001, debug=debug, extra_files=[\"csp.txt\"] if debug else None)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nFlask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debug Mode](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/#debug-mode)\n- [Flask Documentation: Deploying to Production](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/deploying/)\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d6aa8297-1187-36a5-8883-8a671755c279",
              "name": "Debug Mode Enabled In Production Environment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis is an active debug mode configuration issue. In Python Flask applications, running the development server with debug enabled exposes detailed error pages, stack traces, local variables, and other internal state that can reveal sensitive information to an attacker.\n\nIn the shown sink, app.run(debug=True, host='127.0.1.1', port=5000, extra_files='csp.txt') hard-codes debug mode at startup. That is appropriate for local development only, not for deployed environments. The fix is to remove the hard-coded debug flag and control behavior through application configuration or an environment variable so production starts with debug disabled by default.\n\nUsing configuration also reduces the chance of accidentally shipping unsafe settings. In Flask, prefer reading a boolean from the environment and pass that value to app.run only for local use, while keeping the production default set to False.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not hard-code debug=True in Flask startup code. Default debug mode to disabled and enable it only in local development through environment-based configuration. For deployed environments, run the application behind a production WSGI server and ensure detailed error pages are not exposed to users. Keep exception details in server-side logs instead of returning them in HTTP responses.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nimport os\n\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n\ndef env_bool(name: str, default: bool = False) -> bool:\n    value = os.getenv(name)\n    if value is None:\n        return default\n    return value.strip().lower() in {\"1\", \"true\", \"t\", \"yes\", \"y\", \"on\"}\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    debug_enabled = env_bool(\"FLASK_DEBUG\", default=False)\n    app.run(\n        debug=debug_enabled,\n        host=\"127.0.1.1\",\n        port=5000,\n        extra_files=[\"csp.txt\"]\n    )\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nflask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [Flask Documentation: Debugging Application Errors](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/debugging/)\n- [Flask Documentation: Configuration Handling](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/config/)\n- [OWASP: Improper Error Handling](https://owasp.org/www-community/Improper_Error_Handling)\n- [CWE-489: Active Debug Code](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-489",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/489.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-489"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e4de0cbb-835e-318a-9b97-e5aba8c8971e",
              "name": "Sql Injection Via String Formatting",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in a database write operation. This code builds an INSERT statement by interpolating values directly into the SQL string before passing it to execute(), which allows untrusted input such as username or password to change the structure of the query.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, string formatting with %, .format(), f-strings, or concatenation must not be used to assemble SQL with data values. The fix is to keep the SQL text static and pass user-controlled values separately as query parameters so the database driver handles quoting and escaping correctly.\n\nFor this sink, replace the formatted INSERT string with a parameterized statement and provide the values as a tuple in the second argument to execute(). This preserves the intended data types and prevents attacker-supplied input from being executed as SQL.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nUse parameterized queries for every database operation that includes variable data, including INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and SELECT. Keep SQL command text constant and bind values through the database driver's parameter API instead of formatting them into the string.\n\nValidate input for business rules such as username length and allowed characters, but do not rely on validation as a substitute for parameterization. Also store passwords with a strong password hashing function such as bcrypt, Argon2, or PBKDF2 rather than inserting plaintext passwords into the database.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\nc.execute(sql, (username, password, 0, 0, \"\"))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nsqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [PEP 249: Python Database API Specification v2.0](https://peps.python.org/pep-0249/)\n"
              },
