            {
              "id": "e5c8ffba-5e76-303e-b9de-c35341f71f8b",
              "name": "Insecure Usage Of Temp File Or Directory",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure temporary file usage. This code starts a Python web application with an SSL certificate and private key loaded from predictable paths under /tmp. Files in shared temporary directories are vulnerable to tampering, replacement, symlink attacks, and unintended disclosure if permissions are not tightly controlled.\n\nIn this sink, the private key path is especially sensitive. An attacker on the same system may be able to pre-create, replace, or read files in /tmp depending on filesystem protections and process privileges. The call also enables debug mode, which is not appropriate for production-facing TLS service startup. Store certificate material in a dedicated non-temporary directory with restrictive permissions, and run the server without debug enabled.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nDo not place certificates, private keys, session files, or other security-sensitive assets in world-writable temporary directories such as /tmp. Use a dedicated application-owned directory outside temporary storage, set ownership to the service account, and restrict the private key to owner-only permissions such as 0o600. If temporary files are truly required elsewhere in the application, create them with Python's tempfile module and keep handles open to reduce race conditions.\n\nDisable debug mode for deployed services. Prefer terminating TLS in a production-grade web server or reverse proxy, or at minimum ensure the Python process reads key material from stable, access-controlled paths. Validate file existence, type, and permissions before starting the listener so the application fails closed when TLS assets are misconfigured.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\n\nfrom flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\ncert_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls/server.crt\")\nkey_path = Path(\"/etc/myapp/tls/server.key\")\n\nfor path in (cert_path, key_path):\n    st = path.stat()\n    if not path.is_file():\n        raise RuntimeError(f\"Missing TLS file: {path}\")\n    if path == key_path and (st.st_mode & 0o077):\n        raise RuntimeError(\"TLS private key permissions must be restricted to the owner\")\n\napp.run(\n    debug=False,\n    host=\"127.0.0.1\",\n    ssl_context=(str(cert_path), str(key_path)),\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport os\nfrom flask import Flask\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-377: Insecure Temporary File](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html)\n- [CWE-378: Creation of Temporary File With Insecure Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html)\n- [Python tempfile — Generate temporary files and directories securely](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html)\n- [Flask Development Server](https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/server/)\n- [Werkzeug Serving Documentation](https://werkzeug.palletsprojects.com/en/stable/serving/)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-377",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/377.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-378",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/378.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-377",
                  "CWE-378"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e6f9ac4e-dc91-35df-9aae-ae99e96babc6",
              "name": "SQL Injection Via Raw SQL Query Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection in a database write operation. This code builds an INSERT statement by formatting untrusted values directly into the SQL string before execution. In Python, string interpolation does not separate code from data, so a crafted username or password can change the meaning of the query.\n\nFor this sink, the fix is to use the database driver's parameter binding instead of percent-formatting the SQL. Pass placeholders in the statement and provide the values as a separate argument to execute(). This ensures the driver encodes values safely and treats them as data, including quotes and other special characters.\n\nIf this code is using sqlite3 or another DB-API driver directly, use that driver's parameter style consistently. If the application uses SQLAlchemy, prefer bound parameters with text() or use the ORM/Core expression APIs instead of composing raw SQL strings manually.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nNever concatenate or interpolate untrusted input into SQL statements. Use parameterized queries for all dynamic values, including values in INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and SELECT statements. Keep SQL structure static and pass user-controlled data separately through the driver.\n\nUse the placeholder syntax required by the Python database library in use. For sqlite3, use ? placeholders. For other DB-API drivers, use their documented parameter style rather than Python string formatting. If SQLAlchemy is available, prefer text() with bound parameters or the ORM/Core query builders for safer and clearer query construction.\n\nIn addition, validate input for expected type and length, enforce least-privilege database permissions, and avoid storing plaintext passwords. Passwords should be hashed with a strong password hashing function before insertion into the database.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nsql = \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\"\nc.execute(sql, (username, password, 0, 0, \"\"))\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\nfrom sqlalchemy import text\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 module documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n- [SQLAlchemy Textual SQL with bound parameters](https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/20/core/sqlelement.html#sqlalchemy.sql.expression.text)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "eb26927c-520e-3b00-83e0-d5946d693832",
              "name": "SQL Injection Through String-Based Query Construction",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nSQL injection through string-built database queries. This code constructs an INSERT statement by interpolating Python values directly into the SQL text before calling execute(). If username or password contains quote characters or crafted SQL syntax, the database may interpret that input as part of the command instead of as data.\n\nIn Python DB-API code, the fix is to use parameterized queries and pass values separately from the SQL string. For the sink shown here, replace %-formatting with placeholders supported by the driver and supply a tuple of parameters to execute(). This keeps user-controlled values as bound data, prevents SQL parsing of input content, and also avoids manual quoting bugs.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nNever build SQL statements with string interpolation, concatenation, f-strings, or %-formatting when any part of the data can vary at runtime. Use prepared statements or parameterized execute() calls provided by the Python database driver, and pass user input as a separate argument sequence.\n\nApply the same pattern to SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE statements across the codebase. Validate input for business rules such as length and allowed characters, but do not rely on validation or escaping as a substitute for parameter binding. Store passwords with a dedicated password hashing function rather than inserting raw password values into the database.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n~~~python\nc.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO users (username, password, failures, mfa_enabled, mfa_secret) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?)\",\n    (u, p, 0, 0, \"\")\n)\n~~~\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n~~~python\nimport sqlite3\n~~~\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [Python sqlite3 documentation](https://docs.python.org/3/library/sqlite3.html)\n"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
